{"mode":"human","topic":"What is the gender gap in science? Should we address it? And how?","opinion":"As a man of my years, having lived through so much change and seeing my children grow up to navigate a world far different from Bari when I was young, I find myself looking at this discussion about the gender gap in science with a mix of concern and deep-seated conviction that we must address it. It is not merely a matter of fairness, though that is certainly part of it; rather, it speaks to the very strength and completeness of our collective knowledge. Science, at its heart, is about discovery—about expanding the boundaries of what humanity understands about existence, whether it be the flight of a bird I enjoy watching or the mechanics of the human body itself. When half the population’s brilliant minds are systematically underrepresented in these high-level fields, we are not simply losing potential; we are handicapping our species' ability to solve the great challenges that lie ahead, from climate change to global health crises. To ignore this gap would be a profound act of intellectual self-sabotage.

Addressing it requires more than just encouraging girls to take up science, though that is certainly important. It must be systemic and rooted in changing cultural expectations, which can be stubborn things to move. We need to look first at the foundational educational levels, ensuring that from primary school onward, subjects like physics and advanced mathematics are presented through lenses of diverse experiences and examples. But I believe the real shift must happen in how we view success and contribution itself. The environment in scientific institutions, whether universities or research labs, needs to be one where ideas are judged purely on their merit, not filtered through biases related to gender, background, or any other superficial trait. Furthermore, mentorship plays a critical role. Young women need visible role models—not just famous figures from history books, but active, successful professionals who can show them the day-to-day reality of the field. Seeing someone like that in action makes the path seem less intimidating and more attainable.

